Baird, 1843
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,976,1482]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnov" box="[313,503,976,1002]" firstAuthor="Smirnov" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref11380" refString="Smirnov, N. N. (1996) Cladocera: The Chydorinae and Sayciinae (Chydoridae) of the World. SPB Academic Publishing, Amsterdam, 197 p." type="book" year="1996">Smirnov (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[515,633,976,1001]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Pleuroxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[515,633,976,1001]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pleuroxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most difficult genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stebbing" authorityYear="1902" box="[1079,1219,976,1002]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chydorinae">Chydorinae</taxonomicName>
. Barcoding distinguished two species, both in the north: 
<taxonomicName authority="Frey" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1993" box="[616,855,1016,1042]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Pleuroxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varidentatus">
<emphasis box="[616,792,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. varidentatus</emphasis>
Frey
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Birge. The" authorityName="Birge. The" box="[914,1221,1016,1042]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Pleuroxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulatus">
<emphasis box="[914,1086,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. denticulatus</emphasis>
Birge. The
</taxonomicName>
latter species was recently recorded from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[534,623,1056,1082]" name="Mexico" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(Elías-Gutiérrez 
<emphasis box="[827,885,1056,1081]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
2006). 
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnov" box="[975,1161,1056,1082]" firstAuthor="Smirnov" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref11380" refString="Smirnov, N. N. (1996) Cladocera: The Chydorinae and Sayciinae (Chydoridae) of the World. SPB Academic Publishing, Amsterdam, 197 p." type="book" year="1996">Smirnov (1996)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G.Frey" authorityYear="1993" box="[227,400,1096,1121]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Picripleuroxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[227,400,1096,1121]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Picripleuroxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be raised to a genus level, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Chiambeng &amp; Dumont" box="[847,1201,1096,1122]" firstAuthor="Chiambeng" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="211 - 229" refId="ref8422" refString="Chiambeng, G. Y. &amp; Dumont, H. J. (2004) The genus Pleuroxus Baird, 1843 (Crustacea: Anomopoda: Chydoridae) in Cameroon, Central - West Africa. Annales de Limnologie - International Journal of Limnology, 40 (3), 211 - 229." type="journal article" year="2004">Chiambeng &amp; Dumont (2004)</bibRefCitation>
did not support this shift. The high barcode divergences (&gt;20%) between the two species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[1002,1120,1136,1161]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Pleuroxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1002,1120,1136,1161]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pleuroxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
supports Smirnov’s stance and accords with 
<bibRefCitation author="Sacherova &amp; Hebert's" box="[356,700,1176,1202]" firstAuthor="Sacherova" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="629 - 643" refId="ref11049" refString="Sacherova, V. &amp; Hebert, P. D. N. (2003) The evolutionary history of the Chydoridae (Crustacea: Cladocera). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, 79 (4), 629 - 643." type="journal article" year="2003">Sacherova &amp; Hebert’s (2003)</bibRefCitation>
proposal that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[867,985,1176,1201]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Pleuroxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[867,985,1176,1201]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pleuroxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be divided into several genera. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnov" box="[268,521,1216,1242]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Smirnov" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1617 - 1639" refId="ref11411" refString="Smirnov, N. N., Kotov, A. A. &amp; Coronel, J. S. (2006) Partial revision of the aduncus - like species of Pleuroxus Baird, 1843 (Chydoridae, Cladocera) from the southern hemisphere with comments on subgeneric differentiation within the genus. Journal of Natural History, 40 (27 - 28), 1617 - 1639." type="journal article" year="2006">
Smirnov 
<emphasis box="[377,436,1216,1241]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
(2006)
</bibRefCitation>
concluded that the phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[916,1034,1216,1241]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Pleuroxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[916,1034,1216,1241]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pleuroxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is still not resolved sufficiently to be able to decide on generic or subgeneric boundaries, making it clear that further investigation is required.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,976,1482]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
In general our data for the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stebbing" authorityYear="1902" box="[552,689,1296,1322]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chydoridae</taxonomicName>
agree well with conclusions on generic and species boundaries proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sacherova &amp; Hebert" box="[305,636,1336,1362]" firstAuthor="Sacherova" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="629 - 643" refId="ref11049" refString="Sacherova, V. &amp; Hebert, P. D. N. (2003) The evolutionary history of the Chydoridae (Crustacea: Cladocera). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, 79 (4), 629 - 643." type="journal article" year="2003">Sacherova &amp; Hebert (2003)</bibRefCitation>
. For example 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[806,876,1336,1361]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[806,876,1336,1361]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Alona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not monophyletic, and should be partitioned into more than two genera. Part of this work has been done, e.g. the proposal of the new genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smirnov" authorityYear="1989" box="[1309,1397,1376,1401]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Leberis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1309,1397,1376,1401]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Leberis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnov" box="[151,340,1416,1442]" firstAuthor="Smirnov" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="51 - 58" refId="ref11339" refString="Smirnov, N. N. (1989). Tropical cladocera. 2. New species of the families Chydoridae, Macrothricidae and Moinidae from tropical Australia. Zoologische Zhurnal, 68 (7), 51 - 58." type="journal article" year="1989">Smirnov (1989)</bibRefCitation>
, but work remains as shown in the case of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sars" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[841,1025,1416,1441]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentifera">
<emphasis box="[841,1025,1416,1441]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Alona dentifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The deep divergences found in all groups confirm the hypothesis of an ancient origin for all chydorid lineages.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
